english:
  title: 'On the Four Plants: A Gift of Discourse to Lee Pae-ji'
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Buddhist monk Chuk Bun of the Cao Xi lineage has recently gained renown for his skill in calligraphy and painting. My colleague Lee Pae-ji obtained a scroll bearing four plants painted by this master—orchid, bamboo, plum, and cymbidium—and brought it to show me, saying: "My love for this is not love of the painting itself, but love for what is painted: the orchid, bamboo, plum, and cymbidium. I cherish the orchid for its fragrant virtue, the bamboo for its steadfast integrity, the plum for its purity, and the cymbidium for its grace. I hang it where I can see it throughout the day. It can be admired but never defiled—as if I stood among the nine valleys and hundred acres with Bamboo as my companion and Plum as my friend. The ancients took satisfaction in the meaning and did not seek mere appearance. What do you think of this?"

    I replied: "Ah, how profound! Your affection aligns with the wisdom of the ancient sages. The Book of Changes speaks of the orchid; the Book of Documents records the plum; the Book of Poetry and the Rites speak of bamboo; the Songs of Chu sing of orchid and cymbidium—all scattered through the classics and hundred schools of thought. Among all plants worthy of love, there are many, yet none shine forth like these four. You say truly that these are the supreme rarities of heaven and earth, deserving of human admiration. Yet when people love things, each is drawn according to their nature. The love of Zang Wenzhong for marsh grass and Wang Rong for the cherry reveal their lack of benevolence and faith. But when I encounter Pae-ji's gentle speech, harmonious bearing, upright character, and resolute manner, my heart is moved to love and delight. Truly, he is a man of virtue! Thus he does not pursue what Zang and Wang pursued, but loves only these four. What dwells within him mirrors what dwells within them. He recognizes what is worthy of love and loves it—not by chance acquiring these paintings, but by the nature of what he is.

    Consider: my virtue should touch the spirits and earn people's admiration, like the orchid's fragrance. My resolve should be immovable as the bamboo's steadfast strength, unmoved by fortune or poverty. I should embody the plum's clarity and the cymbidium's grace. This is why the heart's affection stirs inevitably—it cannot be suppressed.

    If Pae-ji will cultivate what resonates within him, seeking guidance in the words of the sages, engraving them upon his heart, embracing benevolence and adorning himself with righteousness, his virtue will grow ever brighter. Holding firm to rectitude and steadfast integrity, his resolve will deepen. Looking upon the Changes to know its fragrance, he will achieve true friendship. Studying the Documents to blend them like harmonious spices, he will grasp the proper relationship between ruler and minister. Rising to the poetry of grace in the Book of Poetry, he will advance in learning. Grasping the bamboo-like quality in the Book of Rites, he will perfect the vessel of virtue and decorum. As for the way of the poets—breathing in fragrance and tasting subtle flavors, perfuming their very being and adorning their words—this too becomes merely the overflow of a greater cultivation. Why speak only of loving orchid, bamboo, plum, and cymbidium? What is truly lovable does not reside in these four things alone, but dwells complete within us all.

    Let Pae-ji strive ever onward. His given name is Yun-beon, and he hails from Gwang-ju.
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''four plants''—orchid (蘭), bamboo (竹), plum (梅), and cymbidium (蕙)—were classical symbols of virtue in East Asian literati culture, each representing an ideal quality: fragrance/virtue, steadfastness, purity, and grace respectively.'
    - References to Zang Wenzhong and Wang Rong allude to historical figures whose attachments to specific objects revealed their moral failings—a contrast to the virtuous appreciation Pae-ji demonstrates.
    - The elaborate parallel structure in the latter half draws connections between the four plants and the classical texts (the Changes, Documents, Poetry, Rites, and Songs of Chu), suggesting that cultivation through these texts leads to embodying the virtues symbolized by the plants.
